{
  "$schema": "https://railway.app/railway.schema.json",
  "build": {
    "builder": "NIXPACKS",
    "buildCommand": "bun install && cd packages/api && bun run build"
  },
  "deploy": {
    "startCommand": "cd packages/api && bun run start",
    "healthcheckPath": "/health",
    "restartPolicyType": "ON_FAILURE",
    "restartPolicyMaxRetries": 3
  }
}
/*
DEPLOYMENT GUIDE:
a) Push this repository to GitHub.
b) Connect Railway to your GitHub repo.
c) Add Qdrant service in Railway:
   - Create a new service -> Deploy from Docker image -> qdrant/qdrant:v1.7.4
   - Set start command/args if needed, wait for it to expose its port.
d) Add Redis service in Railway:
   - Create a new service -> Database -> Redis (Railway managed add-on)
e) Set all env vars in Railway Variables for the API service:
   - QDRANT_URL=http://<qdrant-internal-url>:6333
   - REDIS_URL=redis://<redis-internal-url>:6379
   - OPENAI_API_KEY=...
   - LANGFUSE_PUBLIC_KEY=...
   - LANGFUSE_SECRET_KEY=...
   - INGEST_API_KEY=...
   - NODE_ENV=production
f) Deploy — Railway auto-builds using the Nixpacks builder or Dockerfile. 
   Note: We adjusted the buildCommand slightly to run `bun install` from the root 
   so it resolves the workspace:* dependencies properly.
g) Connect frontend to Vercel:
   - Import the repo into Vercel.
   - Set the Framework Preset to Next.js.
   - Set Root Directory to `packages/frontend`.
   - Set `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL` to your deployed Railway API URL.
*/
